// Adversarial: Scripted empty input lets the bolt bounce freely under its
// own physics without breaker interference — pure cell-wall proximity geometry.
// The Fortress layout is used because it places cells near the lateral walls,
// creating narrow gaps where a bolt can be in contact with both a cell edge and a
// wall surface in the same tick. This exercises the CellImpactWall dispatch path:
// a cell entity near a wall that the bolt brushes simultaneously, which can trigger
// a secondary wall impact message alongside the primary cell impact.
// Risks: if the dual-contact frame generates two wall-bump messages and the bolt
// velocity is reversed twice (once per message) the net result is a zero-velocity
// or identity transform — NoNaN and NoEntityLeaks detect the fallout.
// 600 frames is enough for the bolt to traverse the full layout geometry multiple
// times and probe all cell-wall proximity corners.
(
    breaker: "Aegis",
    layout: "Fortress",
    input: Scripted((
        actions: [],
    )),
    max_frames: 600,
    disallowed_failures: [BoltInBounds, BreakerCountReasonable, BreakerInBounds, NoEntityLeaks, NoNaN],
    allowed_failures: None,
    debug_setup: None,
    seed: 1111,
)
